None of Horace’s poems excels this in point of power—— and the power herein exhibited is of the highest kind 3 it is power over the passions of pity and terror. The degree of humour admitted is just sufficient to heighten the effectos the more tragic element. The scene is brought before the eye of the reader with a marvellous distinctness. A boy of good birth, as is shown by the toga praetexta and bulla which he wears, has been decoyed or stolen from his home, and carried at night to some house—probably Canidia's. The poem opens with his terrified exclamations‚ as Canidia and her three associate witches stand around him.
